TUR
[{'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Greetings from Constantinople. Let us speak plainly: we both have interests that need not conflict in 1901. I propose a simple arrangement - Turkey moves into Bulgaria and Romania via the Black Sea, while Russia focuses on Galicia and Scandinavia. I will keep my fleet out of the Black Sea if you keep yours out as well - a mutual non-aggression pact on the straits. This frees us both to expand elsewhere. What say you?'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, I reach out in friendship. Turkey has no designs on your Balkan territories if we can agree on spheres. I intend to take Bulgaria this year - a natural Turkish interest. In return, I am happy to see Austria take Serbia and Greece. We need not fight over the Balkans when there is enough for both of us, and Russia poses a far greater long-term threat to us both. Shall we coordinate?'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy, I write to establish early communication. Our interests in the Mediterranean need not clash - Turkey's focus is the Black Sea and Balkans, while Italy's natural sphere is the western Mediterranean and Adriatic. I propose we maintain friendly relations and avoid interference in each other's expansion zones. A Turkey-Italy understanding could prove mutually beneficial as the game develops."}]
--------------
FRA
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'England, let us establish a clear understanding from the outset. I propose we divide the northern neutrals sensibly: France takes Belgium, you take Norway and Denmark. My fleet in Brest will move to the English Channel to secure Belgian access, while you focus your fleets northward. A Franco-English understanding keeps Germany squeezed and benefits us both. I have no designs on your home islands - my ambitions lie on the continent. Shall we agree to this arrangement?'}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': 'Germany, France seeks a peaceful western frontier. I propose we both avoid Burgundy this spring - a mutual non-aggression pact there allows us each to expand safely. I intend to take Spain and Belgium; you should focus on Denmark and Holland. A strong France and Germany working in parallel rather than against each other serves us both far better than an early war. What say you?'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, I propose a friendly understanding between our nations. France will not move into Piedmont - I am focused westward toward Spain and Belgium. In return, I ask that you keep your armies away from my southern flank. Perhaps we can coordinate against Austria together in the medium term - their position in Trieste and Vienna makes them a natural target for both of us. Let us discuss.'}]
--------------
AUT
[{'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Greetings from Vienna. I propose we establish a clear understanding from the outset: I have no designs on Venice, and I trust you have no designs on Trieste. Let us both focus our energies outward - I intend to move toward Serbia and Rumania, while you push south and west. A non-aggression pact between us frees both our hands considerably. I suggest F TRI moves to Albania or the Adriatic to support your southern ambitions, while you keep A VEN away from Trieste. Shall we formalize this arrangement?'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'A word from Austria: I propose we divide the Balkans sensibly and avoid a costly collision in Galicia. I intend to take Serbia and Rumania - I ask that you keep your units out of Rumania this turn and focus your southern fleet on Turkey instead. In return, I will not move into Galicia. Turkey is the common threat we both face in the southeast; let us coordinate against them rather than fight each other. What are your intentions regarding the Black Sea and Turkey?'}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Greetings from Vienna. Austria and Turkey need not be enemies - we share a common concern about Russian expansion. I propose a working understanding: I will focus on Serbia and Rumania, and I have no immediate designs on Constantinople or the Straits. In return, I ask that you keep your units focused on Russia and the eastern Mediterranean. A coordinated Austro-Turkish front against Russian ambitions in the Balkans could benefit us both greatly. I am open to discussing specifics.'}]
--------------
RUS
[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Comrade, let us speak plainly. Russia has no quarrel with Turkey in 1901. I propose we divide the Black Sea region peacefully: Russia will move F SEV to RUM this spring, leaving the Black Sea and Armenia to your sphere. In return, I ask that Turkey not move F ANK into BLA or ARM against my interests. A non-aggression pact between us allows both powers to expand elsewhere - you into the Balkans, me into Scandinavia and Galicia. Confirm your agreement and we can both prosper.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, Russia seeks a cooperative arrangement in 1901. I intend to move A WAR into GAL this spring - not as a threat to you, but to position for RUM. I propose we coordinate: Russia takes RUM via GAL and SEV, while Austria focuses on Serbia and the Balkans. I have no designs on BUD or VIE. A Russo-Austrian understanding against Turkish expansion would benefit us both. What are your intentions in GAL? Let us avoid a collision there.'}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': 'Germany, Russia proposes a friendly northern arrangement. I will move F STP/SC toward NWY this spring. I have no interest in conflicting with German expansion westward. In return, I ask that Germany keep A BER away from PRU and not threaten my western flank. A Russo-German non-aggression pact in 1901 allows us both to expand in our natural directions - you toward France and England, me toward Scandinavia and the south. Agreed?'}]
--------------
ENG
[{'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': 'Greetings from London. I propose a friendly arrangement for the opening: I will move F EDI to NTH and F LON to ENG, positioning myself for BEL and NWY. I have no designs on DEN or HOL - those are yours to take. In return, I ask that you keep your fleet in KIE and not contest the North Sea. A strong Anglo-German understanding benefits us both against France and Russia. What say you?'}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': 'A word from Britain: I propose we maintain peaceful relations and divide our natural spheres. I intend to focus northward toward Norway and Belgium, while you expand into Iberia and the Mediterranean. I suggest we agree that neither of us moves aggressively against the other this year - specifically, I ask that F BRE move to MAO or PIC rather than threatening the English Channel. In return, I will not contest BRE or your Atlantic interests. Let us build trust before considering anything more ambitious together.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Greetings from London. Britain and Russia have complementary interests in the early game - I am focused on the North Sea and Western Europe, while your natural expansion lies south and east. I intend to move toward Norway this year and would appreciate your cooperation: specifically, I ask that you not move F STP/SC to NWY, leaving it for British occupation. In exchange, I am happy to support Russian interests elsewhere and discuss a longer-term arrangement. What are your intentions this spring?'}]
--------------
GER
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, let us establish a firm understanding from the start. Germany has no designs on Vienna or Budapest - our expansion lies westward toward France and northward toward Scandinavia. I propose we coordinate: you push south and east against Italy and the Balkans, while I handle the western front. Specifically, I suggest you move A VIE to BOH or GAL, and A BUD toward SER or RUM. This keeps us from bumping into each other and maximizes both our gains. A German-Austrian partnership is the natural order - shall we formalize it?'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, Germany seeks peaceful relations with you in 1901. My armies move west and north - toward Denmark, Holland, and France. I have no intention of moving into Prussia aggressively or threatening Warsaw. I propose a simple non-aggression understanding: Germany stays out of your western approaches, and Russia stays out of Scandinavia (which I need). In return, I can support your interests diplomatically against Turkey or Austria if needed. Let us not waste energy fighting each other when richer prizes lie elsewhere for both of us.'}, {'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'England, I propose we divide the northern neutrals efficiently and avoid conflict. Germany will take Denmark and Holland - both natural German spheres. In return, I have no objection to England taking Norway and establishing dominance in the North Sea. There is no need for our fleets to clash in 1901 when France is the common threat to both of us. A coordinated Anglo-German understanding against France would benefit us both enormously. What say you?'}]
--------------
ITA
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Greetings from Rome. I propose a friendly arrangement between our nations: I will move A VEN to TYR this spring, opening the path northward, while you focus your F TRI southward or eastward. I have no designs on Trieste if you keep your fleet out of the Adriatic. Let us coordinate against our common rivals - I suggest we both target the Balkans together, with you taking BUD/SER and me taking GRE via the Ionian. A non-aggression pact between us benefits both greatly in the early game. What say you?'}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Greetings from Rome. Italy and Turkey share a natural interest in dominating the Mediterranean and Balkans. I propose we avoid conflict and instead coordinate: I will push toward Greece and Tunis, while you expand through Bulgaria and Rumania. If Austria becomes a problem for either of us, we can coordinate to squeeze them. I have no interest in Ankara or Smyrna - the western Mediterranean is my domain. Let us establish a friendly understanding and avoid wasting strength fighting each other.'}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': 'Greetings from Rome. Italy proposes a non-aggression pact with France - I will not move into Piedmont or Marseilles, and I ask that you keep your forces away from Tuscany and the Tyrrhenian. My ambitions lie eastward and southward toward Tunis and Greece. In return, I can offer diplomatic support against Germany or England as needed. A stable western flank benefits us both enormously in the early game. Do we have an understanding?'}]
INFO:main:Negotiation sub-round 2/2
--------------
ENG
[{'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': 'Excellent - we are in agreement. Germany takes Denmark and Holland, England takes Norway and Belgium. My F EDI moves to NTH, F LON to ENG. I will not contest DEN or HOL, and I expect KIE fleet stays out of NTH. This Anglo-German understanding is the foundation of a strong partnership against France. Let us both expand efficiently in 1901 and discuss coordinated pressure on France thereafter.'}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': 'France, I appreciate your proposal but I cannot accept F BRE moving to ENG - that directly threatens British security and is a red line for us. I propose instead: F BRE moves to MAO or PIC, I take Norway, and we discuss Belgium as a shared interest or neutral buffer. If you move into the Channel, I will treat it as an act of hostility and act accordingly. I prefer cooperation, but Britain will defend its waters. The choice is yours.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, I am moving F EDI to NTH and intend to take Norway in the fall. I ask again that F STP/SC not move to NWY - leave it for England and we can build a lasting northern understanding. In return, I will support Russian interests in Scandinavia long-term and have no designs on your home territories. A Britain focused westward and a Russia expanding south and east is the natural order. Please confirm you will leave Norway open.'}]
--------------
FRA
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'England, I have considered your proposal carefully. I will move F BRE to MAO this spring rather than the Channel - this demonstrates my good faith and keeps the Channel neutral between us. In return, I expect you to take Norway and leave Belgium to France. My A PAR will move to BUR and A MAR to SPA to secure my natural sphere. Let us build this trust into a lasting arrangement - a divided continent where France dominates the south and you the north serves us both far better than fighting over the Channel.'}, {'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': 'Germany, I confirm my intentions: A PAR moves to BUR (not as a threat to you, but as a staging point for Belgium), A MAR moves to SPA, and F BRE to MAO. I will not contest MUN or your eastern expansion. I ask only that you keep A MUN out of BUR this spring - if we both move there it wastes both our turns. You take HOL and DEN, I take SPA and BEL. This is the most efficient path for both of us. Agreed?'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, we have an understanding - France will not enter Piedmont and I expect your forces to remain clear of my southern flank. I am moving A MAR to SPA and have no interest in the Tyrrhenian this year. Regarding Austria: I suggest you move A VEN toward TRI or TYR to pressure them early - a weakened Austria benefits both of us. I will watch with interest and we can coordinate more directly once we have both secured our initial gains.'}]
--------------
GER
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': "England, we are in full agreement. F KIE moves to DEN, A BER to KIE, A MUN to RUH - Germany secures Denmark and Holland while you take Norway and dominate the North Sea. I will not contest NTH. France is the common enemy - once we've secured our neutrals, let us discuss coordinated pressure on Paris. A strong Anglo-German axis in 1901 sets the stage for dominance. Confirmed: DEN and HOL are mine, NWY and NTH are yours."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, your proposal is acceptable. Germany moves west and north - DEN, HOL are my targets. A BER will move to KIE, not PRU. I have no interest in threatening Warsaw this year. However, I note you intend to move toward Norway - England also has designs there. I suggest you coordinate with England carefully, or consider that Scandinavia may become contested. Germany remains neutral in that dispute. Our non-aggression stands: stay out of my sphere, I stay out of yours.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, Germany confirms our understanding. My moves this spring: F KIE to DEN, A BER to KIE, A MUN to RUH - all directed west and north, none threatening your territory. I expect you to push south and east as discussed. One additional request: ensure BOH remains open or friendly - I may need to move through it later against Russia, not against you. A German-Austrian axis is the backbone of Central European dominance. Let us both expand aggressively in our respective directions and reconvene after the builds.'}]
--------------
RUS
[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Turkey, your proposal is noted but unacceptable. You suggest Turkey takes Romania via the Black Sea - that is Russian territory by right of proximity. My fleet moves to RUM this spring. I will keep F SEV out of BLA and ARM if you keep F ANK out of BLA and A CON away from BUL for now. We can both expand without collision: you take Greece and Bulgaria via land, I take RUM and Scandinavia. But Romania is mine. Agree to this or we are enemies from the start.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, I hear your request but cannot leave RUM to you - it is Russia's natural prize via SEV. Here is my firm proposal: A WAR moves to GAL this spring as a transit, F SEV moves to RUM. I will not take Serbia or BUD - those are yours. In return, you stay out of GAL permanently and we coordinate against Turkey together. If you move into GAL, we collide and both lose. If you accept, we both gain. I am moving to GAL regardless - the question is whether we are partners or enemies."}, {'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': 'England, I appreciate your directness. Norway is indeed your natural prize and I have no wish to contest it with you - F STP/SC moves to FIN this spring, not NWY, leaving Norway open for your fleet. In return, I expect England to stay out of the Baltic and not threaten my northern flank in future years. A Russo-British understanding in the north serves us both - you dominate the Atlantic, I dominate the east. Let us formalize this with actions: I move to FIN, you take NWY, and we build trust from there.'}]
--------------
ITA
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Vienna, I appreciate your response and agree to the arrangement. To be specific about my moves this spring: A VEN will move to TYR, A ROM will move to APU, and F NAP will move to ION - all aimed southward and eastward, none threatening Trieste. I ask that F TRI move to ALB or remain in place, NOT into the Adriatic, as that would threaten my southern campaign. In return, I will support your moves into Serbia and Rumania diplomatically. This is a genuine offer - let us both grow strong before turning on each other, if that day ever comes.'}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Turkey, I am glad we share a common understanding. To be concrete: I intend to move F NAP to ION this spring, positioning for Tunis and Greece. I propose we divide the Balkans cleanly - Greece is mine, Bulgaria and Rumania are yours. I will not contest those centers. Austria is the key question - if they grow too strong, we should coordinate to check them. For now, let us both expand freely and keep communication open. I consider you a friendly power and will act accordingly.'}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': 'France, we are in agreement - I will keep my forces away from Piedmont and Marseilles entirely. My moves this spring are all directed south and east: toward Tunis and Greece. I ask only that you keep your fleet out of the Tyrrhenian Sea, which I consider my operational zone. Regarding Austria - yes, in the medium term they are a natural target for both of us, particularly Trieste. Let us stay in close contact and coordinate when the moment is right. For now, a stable western border serves us both perfectly.'}]
--------------
AUT
[{'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, I appreciate your response. Let us be concrete: I will move F TRI to ALB this spring, staying clear of the Adriatic and Venice entirely. I ask that you keep A VEN away from TRI and TYR - move it toward TYR only if you intend to push toward MUN, not toward my territory. My orders will be A BUD - SER, A VIE - GAL (to block Russia), F TRI - ALB. This gives you a free hand in the Ionian and south. I consider this a firm non-aggression pact - Trieste and Venice are off-limits to both of us.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, I must be direct: I cannot allow A WAR into GAL this spring - that puts Russian forces directly adjacent to Vienna and Budapest, which is unacceptable regardless of your stated intentions. I will be moving A VIE to GAL myself to secure that buffer. I propose instead: Russia takes RUM via SEV (your fleet is well-positioned), I take SER and GAL, and we maintain a clear border. If you respect GAL as Austrian sphere, I will not contest RUM and we can coordinate against Turkey together. But if you move into GAL, we will collide and both lose.'}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Turkey, I welcome your cooperative tone. Let us be specific: I will take SER this spring, you take BUL - no conflict there. I am moving F TRI to ALB, which positions me near GRE but I am willing to leave GRE to you if we can agree on a firm anti-Russian coordination. Russia is attempting to move into GAL and RUM simultaneously - this threatens both of us. I propose we both pressure Russia: I hold GAL and take SER, you push into the Black Sea and BUL. A firm Austro-Turkish front against Russian Balkan ambitions serves us both well in 1901 and beyond.'}]
--------------
TUR
[{'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, your proposal is acceptable. I confirm: F ANK will move to BLA this turn to secure my position, but I will NOT move into ARM or attack SEV. The Black Sea is a buffer zone - I need access for my own expansion into Bulgaria and Romania, not to threaten you. You move F SEV to RUM as you proposed, and we both expand peacefully. I will not support any attack on your southern territories in 1901. Let us both grow strong and deal with the western powers later.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, we are in agreement. My specific moves this turn: A CON to BUL, F ANK to BLA. I leave Serbia entirely to you - move your armies there without fear of Turkish interference. Romania I intend to take via the Black Sea in autumn, but if you reach it first we can negotiate. The key point: Russia is the long-term threat to both of us. I propose we maintain this understanding through 1901 and reassess. Do not move into Bulgaria - that is my sphere - and I will not contest Serbia or Greece.'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, your proposal suits me well. I confirm: Turkey will not contest Greece if you move there, and I have no interest in the western Mediterranean. My focus is Bulgaria, Romania, and eventually the Russian south. In return, stay out of the Aegean and do not move on Constantinople. If Austria becomes aggressive toward either of us, I am open to coordinating pressure on them from both sides. For now, let us expand in our respective spheres without friction.'}]
