TUR
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, our coordination continues to serve us both well. This spring I intend to push F BLA into RUM with A BUL providing support - that gives us 2 strength against Russia's F RUM. I need you to hold A SER in place (do NOT move it to RUM or BUL) so it doesn't interfere with my support order. In return, I will not contest GRE or SER - those are yours. Once I take RUM, we can discuss pushing further into Russian territory together. Russia is our common enemy and they are isolated. Confirm you will hold A SER and keep F GRE in place or move it somewhere that doesn't interfere with my RUM attack."}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, I hope we remain on good terms. I am focused entirely on RUM this season - pushing F BLA into RUM supported by A BUL. I have no designs on GRE or the Aegean. I would suggest you consider moving F ION toward the western Mediterranean or Tunis rather than contesting GRE with Austria - you will only bounce each other there. Let Austria have GRE for now; your strength lies in the west and central Med. I remain committed to our understanding: no Turkish interference in your sphere.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, I will be direct: I am attacking RUM this spring with F BLA supported by A BUL. You cannot hold it - A UKR support gives you 2 strength but so does my attack. Rather than waste both our moves in a bounce, consider withdrawing F RUM to SEV and letting me take RUM peacefully. In exchange, I offer a firm non-aggression pact on SEV and ARM - I have no interest in your northern territories. We can establish a stable border at RUM/SEV and both focus our energies elsewhere. Continued resistance only delays the inevitable and weakens us both against Austria and Italy.'}]
--------------
FRA
[{'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "Kaiser, our alliance served us well last year - BEL bounced due to England's interference, but the deal was sound. This spring I propose we coordinate again: I will move A BUR into BEL, and I need your A RUH to support that move. In return, France will support Germany's position in HOL and we can discuss MUN/BER security against Russia. England is the growing threat with their fleet in ENG and NWY - we must secure the Low Countries before they do. Confirm A RUH supports A BUR into BEL and we both gain from this arrangement."}, {'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': "England, I know you've been eyeing BEL, but I must be direct: France has the stronger position to take it this spring with A BUR already adjacent. Rather than contest it and waste both our moves, let us divide the north sensibly - France takes BEL, you consolidate NWY and look toward DEN or STP. Germany is the real threat to both of us with 4 centers and a strong army position. I propose we coordinate against Germany in 1903 once I'm established in BEL. Fighting over BEL now only benefits Germany and Russia."}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy, our non-aggression holds firm. I'm pushing into BEL this spring to secure the north. I'd encourage you to press Austria hard - they have 4 centers and are growing dangerous. With you threatening from TRI and the east under pressure from Russia and Turkey, Austria can be contained. France will stay entirely out of the Mediterranean and Piedmont. Let's coordinate in 1902 to ensure Austria doesn't dominate the Balkans unchecked."}]
--------------
AUT
[{'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy, we need to talk plainly. You hold TRI which was my home center - I want it back eventually, but I'm willing to be patient if we can agree on a clear division of the Balkans. My immediate focus is on RUM and BUL, not TRI. I propose: you stay out of GRE and the Aegean, I stay out of TRI and Venice. We can both profit by coordinating against Turkey - I'll push A SER -> BUL while you bring F ION to pressure CON/AEG. What do you say? A joint Austro-Italian front against Turkey is worth more than us fighting over scraps."}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Turkey, our alignment served us both well in 1901. Now I want to coordinate for Spring 1902. I'm planning A SER -> BUL and F GRE -> AEG to pressure your position - OR, if you prefer, we can work together against Russia instead. I'd rather have you as a partner than an enemy. Offer: if you move A BUL -> RUM (supporting F RUM to hold or advance), I'll leave GRE and focus A BUD -> RUM from the north. We split the Russian position. Alternatively, tell me what you want and let's find a deal. I need to know your intentions before I commit my moves."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, you have A GAL sitting on my doorstep and F RUM blocking natural Austrian expansion. I'm not going to pretend this isn't a problem. However, I'm open to a deal: pull A GAL back to WAR or SIL, and I'll leave GAL neutral and focus my forces southward against Turkey. We both know Turkey is growing fast with 4 centers - BUL, ANK, CON, SMY. A Russo-Austrian front against Turkey makes strategic sense. If you refuse, I'll be forced to contest GAL aggressively while also pushing south. Your choice."}]
--------------
ITA
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, I want to be direct with you: the situation has changed. You took GRE with your fleet, which was the center I needed for my builds. I now hold TRI, which was your home center - we are at an impasse. I propose a pragmatic arrangement: I will support your position in the Balkans against Turkey and Russia if you acknowledge Italian control of TRI. We can both benefit from coordinating against the real threats - Turkey is growing fast with 4 centers and Russia has 6. Let's discuss terms rather than waste units fighting each other."}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Turkey, Italy now holds TRI and has F ION positioned in the Ionian. I intend to push into the Aegean and Eastern Mediterranean - this means we will inevitably compete for GRE and AEG. I propose we divide the region cleanly: Italy takes GRE and TUN, Turkey keeps BUL, CON, ANK, SMY and we coordinate against Austria together. Austria's F GRE is a threat to both of us. If you move A BUL to GRE with my F ION supporting, we eliminate Austria's fleet and split the Balkans between us. Interested?"}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, the stab worked - Italy now holds TRI as you advised. Austria is weakened and angry. I need your continued support: keep pressure on Austria's western flank if possible, and stay out of PIE and TYS - I need those approaches clear for my Mediterranean expansion. In return, I have no interest in MAR or your western holdings. Germany is your problem, Austria is mine. Let's keep this arrangement solid - a strong Italy and strong France together can dominate the board."}]
--------------
ENG
[{'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "Good morning from London. Last autumn's coordination failed - BEL bounced three ways with France's A BUR and your A RUH both contesting. We need to fix this now. My proposal for Spring 1902: I move F ENG to BEL, you support with A RUH. That secures BEL for England. Meanwhile, your F SKA can move to NTH or hold, and A HOL holds. I'll move F NWY to hold or STP/NC to threaten Russia. France is the common threat - they have 5 centers already and will grow further if unchecked. Confirm you'll support F ENG - BEL with A RUH and we maintain our axis."}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "The BEL situation last autumn was a mess - three-way bounce benefiting no one. I want to resolve this cleanly. I'm willing to support you into BEL this spring if you agree to a firm non-aggression pact: no French fleet in ENG channel, no moves against British interests, and we coordinate against Germany together. Specifically: I move F ENG to BEL with your A BUR supporting, you get the center. In exchange, France commits to moving F SPA/SC away from MAO and toward the Mediterranean. This is a genuine offer - respond with your intentions."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, I want to maintain our cordial understanding. I'm keeping F NWY in place this spring - no threat to SWE or STP. I'd appreciate you keeping F SWE out of SKA and NTH. The real threat to both of us is Germany's growing position - they have HOL, DEN, SKA fleet, and are well-positioned. I'm focused on the western situation for now. Let's keep our northern arrangement stable and revisit cooperation opportunities as the situation develops."}]
--------------
RUS
[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Your attempt to take RUM last fall failed, as I predicted it would. F RUM holds with A UKR support - you cannot break it with F BLA alone. This season I intend to press the issue further. I am willing to offer you a genuine partition: you keep BUL and CON, I keep RUM and SEV, and we establish a Black Sea non-aggression pact. The alternative is continued conflict that benefits only Austria and the western powers. Make your choice - cooperation or mutual exhaustion while others grow strong.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Your coordination with Turkey against me has failed - RUM held and will continue to hold. I now have A GAL positioned directly adjacent to BUD and VIE. I suggest we reconsider our relationship. I am willing to withdraw A GAL to WAR in exchange for a genuine non-aggression pact and your agreement to pressure Turkey in the Balkans rather than coordinating with them against me. Italy has TRI - that is your real problem, not Russia. I can support your efforts to retake TRI if you turn south against Turkey. Respond with your intentions.'}, {'recipients': ['ENG', 'GER'], 'body': 'Gentlemen, our northern arrangements continue to serve us well. GER, I remain out of PRU and SIL as promised. ENG, NWY is yours and I have no designs on it. I intend to focus my energies southward against Turkey and Austria this season. I would ask only that neither of you move against SWE or STP - in return I will continue to respect your western spheres and we can all grow without conflict. Let us confirm this understanding holds for 1902.'}]
--------------
GER
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': "England, I want to be direct with you about the current situation. I hold HOL and SKA, you hold NWY. I propose we coordinate against France - they've grown to 5 centers and are a serious threat. I can push A RUH into BEL and A HOL supports, while you bring F ENG to support or threaten from the north. France in BUR with an army is aggressive posturing toward both of us. Let's squeeze them together - you take BRE eventually, I take PAR. What do you say to a formal Anglo-German front against France this year?"}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, our non-aggression arrangement has served us both well. I note you hold SWE, RUM, GAL - impressive expansion. I have no designs on your territories. I'm focused entirely westward against France. I'd ask only that you keep A GAL away from BOH/SIL - those are my buffer zones. In return, Germany will not contest SWE or any Russian interests in the north. I think we can both grow substantially if we avoid friction with each other and focus on our respective fronts."}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, I'll be honest - last fall I took BEL myself rather than supporting you in, because the opportunity was there and I had to take it. I understand if you're frustrated. But consider: we are both threatened by England's naval dominance. I propose a genuine arrangement now - Germany focuses on BEL and the north, France focuses on Iberia and the Mediterranean. I will not push into BUR if you pull back from it. A RUH can hold, A HOL can hold. Let's establish a real border and both grow without fighting each other while England watches and profits."}]
INFO:main:Negotiation sub-round 2/2
--------------
ENG
[{'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "Confirmed - let's execute the Anglo-German front against France. My orders this spring: F ENG moves to BEL. I need you to support with A RUH - that's the critical move. A HOL holds to secure your center. F NWY holds or moves to threaten Russia's STP if needed. If you support F ENG into BEL, I gain the center and France is squeezed from both sides. In return, I'll support your future moves against France and we coordinate on BRE and PAR in 1903. This is the moment - confirm A RUH supports F ENG into BEL and we execute together."}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, I've considered your proposal carefully, but I cannot accept France taking BEL while Germany sits at 4 centers threatening both of us. My fleet is moving to BEL this spring - if you support with A BUR, we both benefit from a coordinated move and can discuss how to divide the spoils fairly. If you contest it, we both lose and Germany laughs. The smarter play is to let me take BEL now, and I commit to supporting French expansion against Germany in 1903 - specifically coordinating against HOL and RUH. Your F SPA/SC should move toward the Mediterranean where France has real opportunities. Work with me, not against me."}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, our northern understanding holds - F NWY stays put and I have no designs on SWE or STP this season. I'm focused entirely on the western situation with France and Germany. Your southern campaign against Turkey and Austria sounds productive - I wish you success there. Let's keep the north quiet and revisit opportunities for deeper cooperation once we both consolidate our positions."}]
--------------
GER
[{'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': "England, I cannot support F ENG into BEL - that gives you the center, not me. Here is what I will do instead: A RUH moves to BEL directly, A HOL supports A RUH into BEL. This secures BEL for Germany. In exchange, I will not contest NWY and F SKA will hold or move to NTH to support your northern position. France is the real threat - once I have BEL we can coordinate against them properly. I need BEL to grow; you have NWY. Let's not fight over scraps while France sits at 5 centers."}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': 'France, I appreciate the offer but I cannot support A BUR into BEL - that gives you a sixth center and makes you the dominant power on the continent. I am taking BEL myself with A RUH, supported by A HOL. However, I am genuinely offering you this: I will not push into BUR, PAR, or any French territory this year. A HOL supports A RUH to BEL, then I hold. If you pull A BUR back to PAR or MAR, we establish a stable border and both focus elsewhere. Fight me over BEL and we both lose while England profits.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, our arrangement holds perfectly. I am moving A RUH to BEL and A HOL supports - purely westward expansion as promised. F SKA will move to DEN to secure that territory. I have no interest in SWE, STP, or anything in your sphere. Keep A GAL away from SIL and BOH and Germany remains your reliable western partner. The east is yours to dominate - focus on Turkey and Austria while I handle France and England.'}]
--------------
AUT
[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Turkey, I've considered your proposal carefully. I will NOT move A SER to RUM or BUL this spring - I'll use it to hold position and potentially support your attack. However, I need something concrete in return: confirm you will not move A BUL into SER or GRE, and that F BLA stays focused on RUM. My F GRE will move to AEG to give us both flexibility in the eastern Med. If your F BLA takes RUM, we split Russia's southern position and I'll push A BUD toward GAL next. This is a genuine offer - let's execute it cleanly."}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy, I hear you on TRI - let's be pragmatic. I will not attack TRI this spring, and I acknowledge you hold it for now. But I need you to commit to staying out of GRE and the Aegean entirely - F ION stays away from GRE and AEG. In exchange, I'll coordinate with you against Turkey: my F GRE moves to AEG, your F ION can move to EAS or support from ION. Turkey has 4 centers and is growing - they're the real threat to both of us in the south. TRI can be resolved diplomatically later; Turkey cannot be allowed to dominate the Med. Deal?"}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, your offer is interesting but I need action, not words. If you genuinely want an alliance, move A GAL to WAR or SIL this spring - that's the proof I need. In return, I will not enter GAL and will redirect my pressure southward against Turkey. F RUM is yours to hold or advance. But if A GAL stays adjacent to BUD and VIE, I have no choice but to treat you as hostile and coordinate accordingly. The ball is in your court - a genuine withdrawal buys you a genuine partner against Turkey."}]
--------------
ITA
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, I hear your proposal and I'm willing to work with it. My moves this spring: F ION will move toward TUN to secure that neutral center, A APU repositions defensively. I have no intention of pushing into GRE or AEG this season - that's your sphere. In return, keep your units out of TRI and the Adriatic. The real threat is Turkey pushing north and Russia expanding west - let's coordinate A SER against BUL while I pressure from the sea. A joint front makes sense. TRI can be a long-term negotiation; for now let's both profit from the Turkish collapse."}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': "Turkey, your message is noted and I appreciate the clarity. I agree - F ION moves to TUN this season, securing that neutral center for Italy. I have no plans to contest GRE with Austria right now. However, I want to be clear: if Austria's F GRE becomes a threat to either of us in the Aegean, we should coordinate to remove it. For now, focus on RUM, I'll focus on TUN and the western Med. Our understanding holds - no Turkish interference in my sphere, no Italian interference in yours."}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': "France, confirmed - our arrangement holds. I'm moving F ION to TUN this season to secure that build, and positioning for continued Mediterranean expansion. Austria has proposed a temporary truce which I'm entertaining to avoid a two-front problem, but I haven't forgotten their 4 centers. Keep pressing in the north - if you can tie down Germany, I can focus entirely on the Balkans and eastern Med in 1903. Stay out of PIE and TYS and we remain solid partners."}]
--------------
RUS
[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Your math is wrong, Turkey. F BLA supported by A BUL gives you 2 strength - but F RUM supported by A UKR also gives me 2 strength. The attack bounces and you waste your moves while Austria watches and grows. I am not withdrawing from RUM. My offer stands: BUL and CON are yours, RUM and SEV are mine, Black Sea non-aggression. If you insist on attacking, we both stall while Austria consolidates GRE and SER and Italy holds TRI. That serves neither of us. Accept the partition and we both turn our strength elsewhere.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, I hear your proposal but I will not withdraw A GAL to WAR - that leaves me exposed. Here is my counter: A GAL stays in GAL as a neutral buffer, neither of us moves into the other's centers this season. You focus south against Turkey and retake TRI from Italy - I will not interfere. In return, I will not move A GAL into BUD or VIE. Italy sitting in TRI is an insult to Austria that demands response. Turkey has 4 centers and is growing. Let us both focus our aggression southward and stop threatening each other - the western powers will dominate if we exhaust ourselves here."}, {'recipients': ['ENG', 'GER'], 'body': "Confirmed - our northern arrangement holds. F SWE will not enter SKA or NTH, and I remain out of PRU, SIL, and BOH as promised. ENG, I agree Germany's position warrants watching - their fleet in SKA and army in HOL is a strong western posture. GER, I will respect your buffer zones in BOH and SIL. I am directing my full attention south against Turkey and Austria this season. Let us all grow in our respective directions without friction."}]
--------------
TUR
[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, I see your proposal clearly - you are threatening to take BUL while offering cooperation against Russia. Let me be equally direct: if you move A SER to BUL, you will find my A BUL holding with F BLA support, and you will bounce while Russia laughs. The smarter play is what I already proposed: I take RUM with F BLA supported by A BUL, you hold A SER and F GRE, and we both gain. I am executing F BLA - RUM, A BUL S F BLA - RUM this turn. Do NOT move A SER to BUL or RUM - it will only cause a bounce that helps Russia. Hold your position, let me take RUM, and next season we coordinate a deeper push into Russian territory together. This is the path to mutual expansion.'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, your proposal to jointly take GRE from Austria is interesting but premature - Austria is my buffer against Russia right now and I need them occupied in the Balkans, not eliminated. However, I am open to a future arrangement. This season I am focused entirely on RUM. I strongly advise you move F ION toward TUN rather than AEG - Austria has F GRE and A SER, you will not take GRE alone, and a bounce wastes your move. Take Tunis, build a fleet, and then we can discuss the Aegean together from a position of strength. I remain committed: no Turkish units in the Aegean or western Med.'}, {'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': 'Russia, your offer of partition at RUM/SEV is simply asking me to accept the status quo while you consolidate. That is not a deal - that is surrender. I am attacking RUM this turn with full support. If A UKR supports F RUM hold, we bounce and both waste our moves while Austria grows stronger. The rational choice is to withdraw F RUM to SEV, accept RUM as mine, and we establish a genuine border with mutual non-aggression on SEV and ARM. I will honor that border - I have no need for SEV or your northern centers. But RUM is mine by geography and force. Choose wisely.'}]
--------------
FRA
[{'recipients': ['GER'], 'body': "Kaiser, I appreciate your honesty about last fall - you saw an opportunity and took it, as any shrewd leader would. But now we must be practical: I have A BUR adjacent to BEL and I will be moving there this spring. If you contest it, we both waste our moves while England profits. Here is my genuine offer: France takes BEL, Germany keeps HOL and I will not threaten HOL or RUH. A RUH should hold or move elsewhere - do NOT move it to BEL or we collide and England wins. I am moving A BUR to BEL regardless. The question is whether Germany is my partner in the west or my enemy. Choose wisely - England's fleet in ENG is a threat to you too."}, {'recipients': ['ENG'], 'body': "England, your offer is interesting but the mechanics don't work in my favor - if F ENG moves to BEL and A BUR supports, you get the center, not me. I won't be tricked into supporting you into a supply center I should control. Here is the reality: A BUR moves to BEL this spring and France will hold it. I am willing to offer genuine non-aggression - F SPA/SC moves to the Mediterranean as you request, and I commit no fleet to the English Channel. In return, you leave BEL to France and we coordinate against Germany together starting 1903. Fighting me over BEL only exhausts us both while Russia and Germany grow unchecked."}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': "Italy, our arrangement remains solid - France stays out of PIE, TYS, and all Mediterranean approaches. I'm securing BEL this spring to build strength in the north. Press Austria hard from TRI - with Russia in GAL and Turkey pressing from the south, Austria is squeezed on all sides. If you can take VIE or BUD in 1902, that breaks Austrian power permanently. France will build armies this winter and we can discuss coordinated pressure on Germany or Austria in 1903 depending on how the board develops. Stay strong."}]
