[{'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Turkey, your offer is noted but insufficient. You occupy Sevastopol - my home center - and expect me to withdraw A UKR as a concession? That is backwards. Here is my final offer: withdraw F SEV to BLA this turn, and I will move A UKR to WAR (away from the front) and F RUM holds in place. We establish RUM as the boundary - you keep BUL, GRE, and your Anatolian centers, I keep RUM and SEV. If you refuse and hold SEV, I will attack with F RUM supported by A UKR and retake it by force. I have the strength to do it. The choice is yours - a stable partition or a war that weakens us both while Austria and Italy grow.'}, {'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': 'Austria, I hear your demand but consider the reality: Turkey holds Sevastopol and is expanding through the Balkans. F AEG gives you reach into the eastern Med but Turkey has GRE, BUL, CON, ANK, SMY - they will dominate the south if unchecked. I propose a concrete deal: I move A BUD to GAL this turn, you leave GAL unmolested, and we coordinate against Turkey. Specifically: you move F AEG to support an attack on BUL or GRE, I push F RUM toward BUL/SEV. We split the Turkish centers - you take GRE and BUL, I take SEV and CON. This is worth far more than fighting over BUD. Confirm your agreement and I will execute the withdrawal immediately.'}, {'recipients': ['ENG', 'GER'], 'body': "England and Germany, I confirm continued non-aggression on the northern front. F SWE stays clear of NTH and SKA. Germany, France seizing MUN is alarming - a 5-center France threatens everyone. I support your effort to retake it and will keep my units entirely out of SIL and PRU as promised. England, your point about German naval growth is noted - a balance of power in the west serves Russia's interests. I am fully occupied in the south dealing with Turkey's seizure of Sevastopol and have no capacity or desire to interfere in your affairs. Let us all prosper in our respective theaters."}]
