[{'recipients': ['AUT'], 'body': "Austria, the board situation demands we speak plainly. Russia sits in GAL threatening your northern flank, Turkey holds GRE and BUL pressing from the south, and France is growing dangerously large in the west. I propose a genuine working arrangement: I will move A TYR to support your position against Russia (potentially A TYR - BOH or holding as a buffer), while F TUN moves to ION to threaten Turkey's exposed position in GRE. In exchange, I need you to keep F AEG away from ION and not contest my move toward GRE. Turkey is the common enemy here - they hold SER, GRE, BUL, CON, ANK, SMY - six centers and growing. Let's coordinate specifically: I take GRE with F TUN via ION, you press Turkey from AEG toward BUL. What do you say?"}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Turkey, I know what you did last spring - A SER moved to GRE while you told me to go to AEG. You took GRE for yourself and left me with nothing. I have a long memory. I am now positioned with F TUN and A TYR, and I am coordinating with Austria against your overextended position. You hold six centers but your units are spread thin. Consider this a warning: unless you offer me something concrete - specifically, agreeing that GRE belongs to Italy and supporting my fleet into that sea zone - I will work actively with Austria to dismantle your Balkan position. What can you offer me to avoid this outcome?'}, {'recipients': ['FRA'], 'body': 'France, you are at six centers and I am at three - this imbalance concerns me, but I recognize we have been useful to each other. I intend to move F TUN to ION and push toward GRE this fall, taking it from Austria. A TYR will move toward TRI or VIE depending on Austrian behavior. I need you to confirm F WES stays out of TYS and that you have no designs on my home centers while I push east. In return, I will continue to pin Austria from the west, keeping their attention divided. France growing in Germany is fine by me - just leave the Mediterranean to Italy.'}]
