AUT
[{'recipients': ['RUS'], 'body': "Russia, I am moving F AEG into BUL this fall to take that center from Turkey - this is our coordinated strike. I need you to move F BLA toward CON or ANK to pin Turkey's fleet and prevent any counter. A GAL must hold in place - if you move into BUD or VIE while I am pressing south, our deal collapses and I will be forced to defend rather than attack Turkey. My A BUD moves to RUM this fall as well - I trust A UKR will not contest this. If we both execute cleanly, Turkey loses BUL and faces pressure on two fronts. Confirm F BLA moves toward CON and A GAL holds."}, {'recipients': ['TUR'], 'body': 'Turkey, I have heard your ceasefire proposal but I cannot accept terms that leave you holding GRE permanently - that is my supply center and I need it back. Here is my counter: I will move F AEG to BUL/SC this fall, not toward GRE or CON. If you withdraw A GRE to SER voluntarily, I will support your hold on BUL and we can present a united front against Russia. If you refuse, I take BUL and Russia takes ANK - you will be squeezed from both sides simultaneously. Russia has already confirmed to me they are moving F BLA toward your coast. The choice is yours: give back GRE and keep BUL with my support, or lose both.'}, {'recipients': ['ITA'], 'body': 'Italy, I appreciate the offer but I cannot agree to you taking GRE - that is my center and I am reclaiming it. Here is what I propose instead: F TUN moves to ION as a show of force against Turkey, A TYR holds or moves to BOH to buffer against any Russian move through Bohemia. I will press F AEG toward BUL while A BUD takes RUM. If Turkey is squeezed from multiple directions they will collapse quickly. Keep F ION away from AEG and away from GRE - I am handling that front. In return I guarantee TRI and VEN remain untouched by Austrian forces. This is a clean division: you take the western Balkans eventually, I take the eastern Aegean.'}]
